Project: Prosper Loan Data¶

by Eleftherios Kokkinis¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this project, we will be analyzing Loan Data from the Prosper peer-to-peer lending markeplace. Our dataset contains information for about 114.000 loans and 84 different features for each. First we intent to wrangle and clean some of the issues that our data may have. Then we will pose some questions which we will attempt to answer by performing exploratory data analysis practices and creating several visualizations.

Some important features that we will have to keep an eye on include:

  • LoanOriginalAmount: The origination amount of the loan.
  • LoanOriginalDate: The date the loan was originated.
  • MonthlyLoanPayment: The scheduled monthly loan payment
  • LoanStatus: The current status of the loan: Cancelled, Chargedoff, Completed, Current, Defaulted, FinalPaymentInProgress, PastDue.
  • BorrowerAPR: The Borrower's Annual Percentage Rate (APR) for the loan.
  • BorrowerRate: The Borrower's interest rate for this loan.
  • Term: The length of the loan expressed in months.
  • EstimatedReturn: The estimated return assigned to the listing at the time it was created.
  • ProsperScore: A custom risk score built using historical Prosper data. The score ranges from 1-10, with 10 being the best, or lowest risk score. Applicable for loans originated after July 2009.
  • ListingCategory: The category of the listing that the borrower selected when posting their listing.
  • BorrowerState: The two letter abbreviation of the state of the address of the borrower at the time the Listing was created.
  • Occupation: The Occupation selected by the Borrower at the time they created the listing.
  • EmploymentStatus:The employment status of the borrower at the time they posted the listing.
  • DebtToIncomeRatio: The debt to income ratio of the borrower at the time the credit profile was pulled.
  • IncomeRange: The income range of the borrower at the time the listing was created.
  • StatedMonthlyIncome: The monthly income the borrower stated at the time the listing was created.
  • Recommendations: Number of recommendations the borrower had at the time the listing was created.
  • Investors: The number of investors that funded the loan.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Our original dataset contained 113.937 total loans with information broken down to 86 different variables. Most of them were numeric and several of them categorical. However, many variables were not going to add something to our analysis and we removed for the shake of simplicity of the dataframe. Our new table containes just 18 variables, with the categorical ones being:

  • LoanStatus
  • BorrowerState
  • Occupation
  • EmploymentStatus
  • IncomeRange
  • ListingCategory

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features that we are interested in exploring more are the ProsperScore, LoanStatus the BorrowerAPR and the LoanOriginalAmount. Specifically, we will attempt to find out what factor/s affect the values of these variables

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

According to traditional finance we should expect that the interest rate, BorrowerAPR to increase as the size of loan increases, to accommodate the increased risk associated with the loan. It is also expected that the DebtToIncomeRatio, the Occupation and the Recommendations may have somethind to do with the LoanStatus and the ProsperScore. The Listing Categories could be influencing the LoanOriginalAmount and the Investor may be more when the EstimatedReturn is higher.

Univariate Exploration¶

We will begin our analysis by checking the distributions and the value counts of individual variables

LoanOriginalAmount - BorrowerAPR - ProsperScore - Distributions¶

We will check the distribution of the Loan amounts, Borrower APM and Prosper Score to get an overview of these features.

In [995]:
sb.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(10,6)})

columns=['LoanOriginalAmount','BorrowerAPR','ProsperScore']
for i in columns:
    sb.histplot(df,x=i,bins=50)
    plt.title(i+' Distribution')
    plt.show();

We can see that the Loan Amounts form a right-skewed distribution which means that the majority of the loans were relatively small amounts. Some outliers however exist at the amounts of 10000, 15000, 20000, 25000 and 35000.

Borrower's APR distribution seems to be multi-modal with several peaks at about 0.1, 0.17, 0.21, 0.3 and 0.36. Specifically 0.36 accounts for the APR of over 7000 loans which makes it by far the most popular Borrower's APR

Finally, the ProsperScore forms an almost perfect normal distribution with a mean of 6.

Discussion¶

Our distributions were mostly right-skewd which was a good indication on what people are most likely to receive loans. Most people's stated income goes up to 30000, although there are some extreme outliers as well. Those were spotted and removed. We also noticed that for most people the Debt to Income ratio was relatively low as well. Most people who received a loan were Employed and the most popular listing was about Debt Consolidation. An intereting observation was that the amount of given loans follows a pattern and there are significantly higher number of loans given for the amounts of 5000,10000,15000,20000,25000,35000. In addtion to that, the Borrower's APR seem to be multi-modal and is peeking on various different points. Other than those observations, no other unusual things were spotted and no further actions were taken.

Observations:¶

We notice some interesting correlations here, some of which were expected and some were not.

  • ProsperScore seee to have a high negative correlation with the Borrower's APR and the Estimated Loss
  • In turn, the Borrower APR has a high positive correlation with the Estimated Return and the Estimated Loss, above 0.8
  • The Original Loan Amount has an almost perfect positive correlation with the Monthly Loan Payments which makes sense since higher a higher loan amount would need higher payments to accommodate it.
  • The Loan Amount is also negatively correlated with the Borrower's APR which is an observation that differs from our hypothesis that higher Loan amounts would also mean higher interest rates.

Other than these features, the rest of the observations seem relatively weak.

Loan Amount - Listing Categories, Employment Status and Loan Status¶

In [982]:
def violinplots(df,cols,y):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=4, ncols=1, figsize=(10, 30))
    for name, ax in zip(cols, axes):
        sb.violinplot(data=df, x=name, y=y, ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(name)
        ax.set_ylabel(y)
        ax.tick_params(rotation=90)
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.6)
In [983]:
violinplots(df,['ListingCategory','EmploymentStatus','LoanStatus','IncomeRange'],'LoanOriginalAmount')

In all the violin plots, we are able to spot that the big bulk of the Loan Amounts goes up to 15000. However, larger amounts seem to be given for Debt Consolidation. In addtion, people with Employed and Full-Time status are also more likely to receive higher amount loans.

The LoanStatus do not seem particularly related to the Loan Amount, although the 'Current' status includes more Loans of higher amounts. Finally, the higher income groups seem to also be getting higher loan amounts which is a rather reasonable observation.

def boxplots(df,cols):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=1, figsize=(15, 12))
    for name, ax in zip(cols, axes):
        sb.boxplot(data=df, x=name, y='BorrowerAPR', ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(name)
        ax.set_ylabel('APR')
        if name=='ListingCategory' or name=="LoanStatus":
            ax.tick_params(rotation=90)
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.4)
In [986]:

Generally, the APR does not look particularly affected by the State of origin of the borrower. However, the states of Maine and Iowa seem to be getting a lower APR overall.

The interesting but expected observation here is that loans with higher ProsperScore are getting a visibly lower APR, while loans with lower score a significantly higher APR. That's reasonable considering that the ProsperScore is also a reflection of the risk that each loan entails.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

We verified a lot of the relationships that we found earlier in a more complete manner. We realized that lower APR means higher ProsperScore while Large Loan Amounts also bear a higher ProsperScore and come from people with high incomes. In addition, we spotted a positive relation between the Estimated Loss and the APR and consequently a negative one with the Prosper Scores. Finally, it was made clear that the Defaulted, Changed off and Completed Loans had a higher Estimated Loss and feature lower Prosper Score.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The results were very intuitive in the sense that they mostly make sense from a financial point of view. Loans with higher Estimated Loss, entail more risk, therefore they have a higher APR and a lower overall ratin and vice versa. Also, people with higher incomes are naturally more in position to take larger loans and have better chances in getting a lower APR and a higher Score.
